Drunk with corruption
My friend Boris was going to leave from my place, drunk.
I therefore suggested to him not to drive.
He asked me why.
« You have drunk », I said to him, « aren't you afraid of the police ? »
Boris replied to me: "No, I possess a Benjamin Franklin document, it always comes in handy."
He showed me his driver's license with the $100 bill slipped next to it.
Of course, I knew that the police take bribes, but I was worried that Boris would run into a police officer who was not corrupt.
"Impossible," Boris declared, "to get into the traffic police department, you have to buy your boss's silence."
If you don't take bribes, how can you buy your boss's silence?
Half of the drivers in Moscow use illegally obtained driver's licenses.
People who try to do things by the book get bogged down in administrative red tape.
Paying 100 dollars, you can drive in the city without any restrictions!
Corruption and embezzlement have always existed in Russia, before and after Lenin's October Revolution.
But never at the record levels we see today.
Everyone accepts bribes, everywhere and for anything.
The only ones who do not accept them are those to whom they are not offered, according to Boris.
Corruption flourishes in most institutions, and the fight against corruption always ends in a catastrophe or abandonment.
The police, prosecutors, customs officers, and even the Kremlin: no one is immune anywhere.
Recently, I was visiting a dacha village in one of the most beautiful suburbs of Moscow.
It was a luxurious place but similar to a gulag with its high-security fences and guards.
Examining the pretentious and poorly decorated houses, I wondered who owned them and was told that one belonged to a deputy mayor of Moscow, another to a famous singer, and another to the son of the Moscow prosecutor.
But the most attractive property belonged to a modest tax official.
Corruption now poses a greater threat to Russia than the Chechen war.
In fact, the Chechen war would not have lasted as long if it had not been led by corrupt generals, officers, officials, and police who sell arms and supplies to the rebels.
Russian television recently showed a bus running between Grozny and Moscow, the same bus that brought 120 kilograms of explosives to Moscow for the Dubrovka Theatre siege, where so many victims lost their lives during the assault meant to free the hostages.
A passenger on the bus covered the explosives with a cloth soaked in acid to prevent customs dogs from detecting them.
A rather useless precaution.
No one controls the buses anymore today.
The driver, who didn't know what he was transporting, said he was stopped 50 times along the way, and every time for the same reason.
A policeman came up to him and asked: "Do you know the price?" and the driver replied: "Of course, I know it," by paying the bribe before leaving.
Without a bribe, the bus would have been delayed for hours at each stop, or even entire days for the journey.
The war against Chechnya continues indefinitely not only because Chechen rebels have allies in Al Qaïda and all "international terrorists" but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, army, civilians who accept bribes, and thieves, who first tax Chechen civilians or simply steal from them, sell arms and explosives to terrorists, maps indicating where the minefields are, and provide rebels with fake documents.
In May of this year, during the explosions in Kaspiisk, terrorists used arms bought from Russian army officers.
The rebels have modern weapons.
Where do they come from?
In the mountains where the rebels hide, there are no gun shops.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers fighting the rebels have their own stockpiles of ammunition, from which the weapons are stolen and sold.
And it's not just weapons: some young officers are selling their own men into slavery.
Russian corruption has reached catastrophic levels, and yet no fight has been launched against this plague.
Punish corruption more harshly?
This would only increase the prices of corruption.
The harsher the punishment, the more one will have to pay to avoid it.
No official wants to fight corruption because they themselves are corrupt.
Thus, those called "ordinary people" view this phenomenon with benevolence.
They say of their mayor "yes, of course, he steals, but look at all he's done for the city!"
Ordinary people don't like honest workers either.
Why?
A train ticket costs 100 rubles, but by paying a small bribe, one can travel for 50 rubles.
The traveler and the controller both benefit from this system.
An honest old grandmother once told me that she had bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The controller stopped her, saying that passengers with a ticket were not allowed on the train!
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you don't want your son to be called up for military service, buy an army clerk and they will cross out your son's name from the list, or bribe a doctor to declare him unfit for military activity.
You can enter any university for a certain price, regardless of your references and diplomas.
You can drive drunk, speed, ignore red lights, as long as Ben Franklin is there to bribe the police.
Alexander Menchikov, the minister of Peter the Great, had understood the impossibility of winning the fight against corruption.
When the disappointed Tsar Peter, tired of Russia's corruption, decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menchikov replied: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects."
In the centuries that have passed since, the situation has worsened.
Removing corruption might leave the state without citizens, but if we don't stop the progression of corruption, citizens will soon be left without a state.
